By way of contrast, in Gabon, young women drop out of school as often for love as they do for financial issues. “School is free in Gabon, but some young people drop out because they choose to get married,” said Comlan Jean-Placide Nougolabi, 26, an ASC coordinator in Pointe Denis, Gabon. “The education I once hoped for has now vanished, in the future I just hope that my children receive the same education I once hoped for.”

The ideas behind the 4H clubs go much further than improving education in the villages. “Villages are the foundation of everything,” Nougolabi explains. “Our projects not only support education, but they also help people to become aware of their needs and their rights. Without awareness, people cannot change anything.” ASC believes that giving new opportunities to young people can change whole villages – that they are an investment in a brighter future, rather than just a way to make life a bit easier right now. “For us, the ideal principle is education,” said Nougolabi.
